        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date of the letter is based on the 1859 watermark on the stationery, and on the year provided in K. M. Lyell ed. 1890, 2: 300.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Horner’s letter has not been found. CD had received a letter from him soon after the publication of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> expressing his general approval of the arguments presented in the book. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 7, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2596.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Leonard Horner, 23 December [1859]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD was in London on 21 and 22 February 1861. On 21 February, he gave an account to the Philosophical Club of the Royal Society of the results to date of his experiments on <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_789.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Bonney 1919</ref>, p. 154). Horner was the chairman of the meeting (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 9, Appendix IV).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Horner was preparing to discuss <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> in his presidential address to the anniversary meeting of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1841.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Geological Society of London</ref> on 15 February 1861 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3868.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Horner 1861</ref>). See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3094.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Leonard Horner, 20 March [1861]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
